lass=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 185<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(9/19/02 1:35:59 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1403.topic&index=45>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_bigsmile.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: The tired good + evil grouping topic.</span><hr size=1> Disclaimer: The opinions contained herein may or may not be in response to any of the prior posts. It's just an airing of thoughts on the old issue of roleplaying.<br>
<br>
I would like to see a set standard. I would like to see it all stated out in a book what each race's history is what their struggles are and what alliances/enemies they have. Going by RL, history will always influence your actions whether or not reacting based on that history is right or wrong. <br>
<br>
In EQ - We are not united enough to create our own racial history. No man is an island. How can you have a racial history when nobody else has that common experience? <br>
<br>
By going by the book, whether EQ manual (which I personally haven't really read in detail) or some other source e.g. Codex of War, players can have a common history.E.g. From Bloody Kithicor you have opposing forces. Now if you RPed having a family from those forces, you might naturally have an inclination to hate the opposing force. The challenge will then be the way you manifest your hatred for them. But if you don't, you can also create an RP explanation of why you don't.e.g. your family was not involved, you think your family was wrong.<br>
<br>
It should not be a straight forward, I am evil therefore I hate all good. It should be I refuse to associate with you because of certain RP reasons. (This is on the verge of touching on the good and evil issues - just to state I don't believe in good, evil, or neutral races. Although I will be suspicious of your motives and may hate you because of historical background, I do not believe that you are evil just because you are a dark elf. I'll believe you are evil when you behave in a way for the purpose of bringing pain and suffering to others.)<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/umadrain.showPublicProfile?language=EN>madrain</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Kerran Lord</span><br>  Posts: 947<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(9/19/02 2:01:04 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1403.topic&index=46>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_bigsmile.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: The tired good + evil grouping topic.</span><hr size=1> Eh, I give up.  I'm not a good enough writer to convey what I really want to say.  I must be messing up somewhere.<br>
<br>
The way I take it is that the good Captain is claiming that anyone who roleplays a racial hatred, or goes by the book in their roleplay, is not a good roleplayer.<br>
<br>
I certainly concede that just by /shouting &quot;High Elves Suxx0rz!&quot; does not mean you are roleplaying.  But, and forgive me if there's just something I'm missing, I do fail to see how Ollias differentiates between the two.<br>
<br>
I'm sorry if I hurt anyone's feelings - I get hotheaded and defensive over people slamming other people's roleplay.  I feel that roleplay of any kind is a boon to the server, and should not be chased off.<br>
<br>
And for the record, in-game I do not roleplay a racial hatred, and have only done so with one character, that character eventually falling in love with a wood elf.  I was once a proud member of Twilight Bastion, and am on good terms with decent number of their members, and am fairly close friends with 2 or 3 of them.  I just don't like to see someone slamming someone else's posts.<br>
<br>
Again, I apologize if I missed something.  I am tired of trying to argue my point, and thus, duck out. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=d1c3b5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub94.ezboard.com/upentapod.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Pentapod</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://members.ozemail.com.au/~pentapod/graphics/a_pod.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>WTB phat newt</span><br>  Posts: 989<br> <font color=#A62A2A>(9/19/02 2:13:26 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub94.ezboard.com/ffirionaviefrm4.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1403.topic&index=47>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.ezboard.com/images/posticons/pi_bigsmile.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: The tired good + evil grouping topic.</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> The way I take it is that the good Captain is claiming that anyone who roleplays a racial hatred, or goes by the book in their roleplay, is not a good roleplayer.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END-->I'm not quite sure where the communication is breaking down, but I am certain this is not what the Captain is claiming.  *I* 'go by the book' in my roleplay (which is to say I play an evil, Innoruuk-worshipping devious scheming Teir'dal who hates non-evils), and I roleplay racial hatred, and I am *quite* certain that if the Captain thought I was not a good roleplayer, I'd've heard about it by now.  I do not believe this is at all what he intended to say, and I can only add that I think you have misinterpreted his intent, madrain.<br>
